04486nam a22007335i 9780814767917DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t19971997nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147679177 a10.18574/nyu/9780814767917.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)548447  a(OCoLC)47010516  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN 7aLIT0000002bisacsh1 aParis, Bernard Jay, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImagined Human Beings :bA Psychological Approach to Character and Conflict in Literature /cBernard Jay Paris. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1997] 4c©1997  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLiterature and Psychoanalysis ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPart I. Introduction -- t1. Applications of a horneyan approach -- t2. Horney's mature theory -- tPart II. Characters and relationships -- t3. A doll’s house and hedda gabler -- t4. The end of the road -- t5. "The clerk's tale" -- t6. The merchant of Venice -- t7. Antigone -- tPart III. Character, plot, rhetoric, and narrative technique -- t8. Great expectations -- t9. Jane Eyre -- t10. The mayor of casterbridge -- t11. Madame Bovary -- t12. The awakening -- t13. Wuthering heights -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of literature's greatest gifts is its portrayal of realistically drawn characters--human beings in whom we can recognize motivations and emotions. In Imagined Human Beings, Bernard J. Paris explores the inner conflicts of some of literature's most famous characters, using Karen Horney's psychoanalytic theories to understand the behavior of these characters as we would the behavior of real people. When realistically drawn characters are understood in psychological terms, they tend to escape their roles in the plot and thus subvert the view of them advanced by the author. A Horneyan approach both alerts us to conflicts between plot and characterization, rhetoric and mimesis, and helps us understand the forces in the author's personalty that generate them. The Horneyan model can make sense of thematic inconsistencies by seeing them as the product of the author's inner divisions. Paris uses this approach to explore a wide range of texts, including Antigone, "The Clerk's Tale," The Merchant of Venice, A Doll's House, Hedda Gabler, Great Expectations, Jane Eyre, The Mayor of Casterbridge, Wuthering Heights, Madame Bovary, The Awakening, and The End of the Road.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCharacters and characteristics in literature. 0aLiteraturexPsychological aspects. 0aLiteraturexPsychology. 0aLiterature. 0aMotivation (Psychology) in literature. 0aPsychoanalysis and literature. 0aPsychology in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107169240 cprintz978081476655240uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814767917.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814767917423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814767917/original  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK